[[Category:Court Ranks of Japan]][[Category:completion tier 4]][[Category: tier 4]] {{Cite_sources_needed|date=August 2015}}
'''Shōnii''' (正二位) is one of the ranks in Japan's [[Ritsuryō]]-based hierarchy and [[Shinkai (divine rank)|Shinkai (divine ranks)]]. It is positioned below ''{{ill|Junior First Rank|ja|従一位|1=Junior First Rank}}'' (従一位) and above ''{{ill|Junior Second Rank|ja|従二位|1=Junior Second Rank}}'' (従二位).<ref>https://www.wakapoetry.net/background/society/court-offices-titles-and-ranks/court-ranks/</ref>
== Overview ==
In the [[Ritsuryō system]], Shōnii corresponds to the positions of [[Sadaijin|Minister of the Left]] and [[Udaijin|Minister of the Right]] under the {{ill|Kan'i sōtō system|ja|官位相当制|1=Kan'i sōtō system}}. When awarded posthumously, the rank is denoted as Zō Shōnii (贈正二位).
During the [[Muromachi shogunate|Muromachi]] and [[Edo period|Edo periods]], the [[Seii Taishōgun|shōguns]] often held this rank while in office. In addition, court nobles of the [[Hulin Houses|middle nobility]], such as [[Dainagon|Major Councilors]] and [[Chūnagon|Middle Councilors]], who did not rise to ministerial positions, could be promoted to this rank.
From the [[Meiji era]] to the pre-war [[Showa era]], Shōnii was a rank conferred on {{ill|8=ja|9=親任官|Shinninkan|Shinninkan=Shinninkan|lt=imperial appointees}}, {{ill|8=ja|9=勅任官|Chokunin|Chokunin=Chokunin|lt=imperial officers}}, and [[kazoku|nobility]]. In terms of [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Japan|orders of merit]], it corresponded to {{ill|8=ja|9=大勲位|Grand Cordon}} or First-Class honors.
Under the [[Constitution of Japan|post-war constitution]], Shōnii is a posthumous honor and is often awarded to individuals who have served as [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Ministers]] or other distinguished leaders.
